"1335–Deceased","1337–Female":"1337–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1275–1319":"1275–1319","1280–Female":"1280–Deceased","Abt 1337":"about 1337","1275":"1275","1297":"1297","Abt 1312":"about 1312","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1403":"1403","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","after 1319":"after 1319","1354":"1354","1331":"1331","about 1335":"about 1335","about 1354":"about 1354","about 1333":"about 1333","1319":"1319","Clithroe, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Chipping, Lancashire, England":"Chipping, Lancashire, England","Chippingdale, Chipping, Lancashire, England":"Chipping, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Singleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and West Yorkshire):","habitational name from Singleton (Lancashire), probably from Old English <i>scingol</i> ‘shingle, wooden roof tile’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Bearers of this surname are said to be descended from Ughtred <i>de Sinleton</i>, holder of lands in Amounderness wapentake (Lancashire) <i>c.</i> 1160–90. This name was first recorded in Ireland in 1308 and firmly established in Louth and Monaghan during the 17th century.","habitational name from Singleton (Sussex), probably from Old English <i>sængel</i>, <i>sengel</i> ‘bundle, tuft’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Singelton","meanings":["English: variant of   Singleton  ."]},{"name":"Shingleton","meanings":["English: late medieval variant of   Singleton  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Singleton was born about 1312, her father, Randle de Singleton, was 39 and her mother, Mabel, was 34. She had at least 4 sons and 2 daughters with Lord Thomas de Knoll Commission of the Peace. She died in 1358, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 47."},"et":{"Abt 1312–1358":"umbes 1312–1358","1312–1358":"1312–1358","1297–1354":"1297–1354","1331–Male":"1331–Surnud","1333–Male":"1333–Surnud","1335–1403":"1335–1403","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1337–Female":"1337–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1275–1319":"1275–1319","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","Abt 1337":"umbes 1337","1275":"1275","1297":"1297","Abt 1312":"umbes 1312","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1403":"1403","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","after 1319":"pärast 1319","1354":"1354","1331":"1331","about 1335":"umbes 1335","about 1354":"umbes 1354","about 1333":"umbes 1333","1319":"1319","Clithroe, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chipping, Lancashire, England":"Chipping, Lancashire, England","Chippingdale, Chipping, Lancashire, England":"Chipping, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1312–1358":"noin 1312–1358","1312–1358":"1312–1358","1297–1354":"1297–1354","1331–Male":"1331–Kuollut","1333–Male":"1333–Kuollut","1335–1403":"1335–1403","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1337–Female":"1337–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1275–1319":"1275–1319","1280–Female":"128